<p>
  The mind is all we have. Every pleasure, every irritation, every sense of a self set
  against the world is shaped by the attention that meets it. Careers unfinished,
  relationships pending, repairs still waiting — none of that cancels the quieter fact:
  experience is always happening now, in a mind that is either clearer or more confused.
</p>

<p>
  Overthinking, in the sense that names this site, is not simply thinking a lot. It is
  thought that keeps elaborating without returning to what is actually present — planning
  as evasion, rumination as identity, cleverness that never lands. The early Buddhist
  texts are unusually precise about that habit. They treat it not as a personality flaw
  but as a trainable pattern: craving, clinging, and the stories the mind builds around
  both.
</p>

<p>
  Nothing here is final. These are notes, not conclusions.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>Not a temple, not a course</h2>

<p>
  These pages are a working record of sitting with the Buddhist tradition long enough for
  parts of it to become usable — not as a scholar cataloguing schools, and not as a
  devotee defending a fixed view. The tradition is old, vast, and internally diverse.
  What appears here draws primarily from the Pali canon — the earliest surviving body of
  Buddhist teaching — while remaining attentive to what later traditions developed,
  contested, and corrected.
</p>

<p>
  This is not a substitute for a teacher, a community, or sustained practice. It is also
  not a worldview to adopt wholesale. The texts themselves often ask to be tested against
  experience rather than believed on authority. Where interpretation hardens into certainty
  on these pages, treat that as a draft that has not yet been revised.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>A diagnosis, not a creed</h2>

<p>
  The Buddha's first discourse after his awakening turned on a single axis: the reality
  of <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>.
  Not as a pessimistic claim that life is worthless, but as a diagnostic starting point —
  if a problem is to be addressed, it has to be named. The Four Noble Truths that structure
  <a href="/suttas/dhammacakkappavattana/">that discourse</a> are less a creed to be
  believed than a framework to be applied: here is what is wrong; here is its cause; here
  is the possibility of its ending; here is the path.
</p>

<p>
  The cause identified is
  <span class="pali" data-pali="tanhā" data-en="craving">tanhā</span> —
  craving, thirst. A meal goes from anticipation to too much; sun on the skin becomes heat;
  shade becomes chill. Wanting and not-wanting trade places all afternoon. This reaching is
  not incidental to suffering; it is its mechanism.
  <span class="pali" data-pali="upadāna" data-en="clinging">Upadāna</span>
  consolidates that thirst into clinging — and from clinging, the continued becoming that
  keeps the pattern running. The tradition also asks that conditioned experience be seen
  through <a href="/concepts/ti-lakkhana/">three characteristics</a> —
  <span class="pali" data-pali="anicca" data-en="impermanence">anicca</span>,
  <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>,
  <span class="pali" data-pali="anattā" data-en="non-self">anattā</span> —
  not as slogans, but as what becomes visible when craving loosens its grip.
</p>

<p>
  The response is not a metaphysical settlement. It is a path — the
  <a href="/concepts/eightfold-path/">Noble Eightfold Path</a>, often seen through the
  <a href="/concepts/three-trainings/">three trainings</a> of
  <span class="pali" data-pali="sīla" data-en="virtue">sīla</span>,
  <span class="pali" data-pali="samādhi" data-en="concentration">samādhi</span>, and
  <span class="pali" data-pali="paññā" data-en="wisdom">paññā</span>.
  Ethics steadies the mind; stillness clarifies seeing; seeing refines how one lives.
  The path spirals. The concepts and suttas on this site take those movements apart; this
  page only needs to name the pressure.
</p>

<blockquote>
  "Monks, I do not say that the attainment of wisdom is all at once. Rather, the
  attainment of wisdom is by gradual training, gradual practice, gradual progress."
  <cite>— MN 70 (adapted)</cite>
</blockquote>

