<h2>On the Pali language</h2>

<p>
  Throughout these pages you will meet words in Pali — the language in which the earliest
  Buddhist teachings were preserved. They appear in an ochre tint with a dotted underline.
  They are not decorative.
</p>

<p>
  English translations of Pali words are always approximations. A word like
  <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>
  is routinely rendered as "suffering," but that misses registers the English word does
  not carry. A word like
  <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">sati</span>
  has been so thoroughly domesticated into wellness culture that meeting it in its
  original context can feel like an introduction to a stranger you thought you knew.
</p>

<p>
  Click any highlighted Pali word for a short note on the term and its closest English
  sense. On larger screens the notes appear in the right margin; on a phone they expand
  inline. Several can stay open at once. The same notes are collected in the
  <a href="/glossary/">glossary</a>.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>Where to begin</h2>

<p>
  If you are not sure where to start, use the
  <a href="/guide/">Guide</a> — a suggested trajectory from orientation through ideas that
  tend to need practice underneath them. For a simple beginning sit, see
  <a href="/concepts/how-to-sit/">How to Sit</a>.
  Beyond that, the site divides into four main sections.
  <a href="/concepts/">Concepts</a>
  takes up core ideas one at a time.
  <a href="/suttas/">Suttas</a>
  looks at specific discourses: what they contain, how they are structured, what they ask
  of the reader.
  <a href="/thoughts/">Thoughts</a>
  is the less tidy section — longer pieces where something is still being worked out.
  <a href="/quotes/">Quotes</a>
  collects passages worth sitting with.
</p>

<p>
  Everything here is a draft in the sense that understanding changes. If something seems
  wrong or is missing important nuance, that is probably because the draft has not caught
  up yet. The path spirals.
</p>
